Pour the @water for the rice{300%ml} into a #medium saucepan{} with a tight-fitting #lid{}.

Stir in the @Basmati Rice{150%g} and @salt{1/4%tsp} and bring to the boil. Once boiling, turn the heat down to medium and cover with the lid.

Leave to cook for ~{10%minutes}, then remove the pan from the heat (still covered) and leave to the side for another ~{10%minutes} or until ready to serve (the rice will continue to cook in its own steam).

While the rice cooks, trim the @Green Beans{80%g}, then cut into thirds.

Peel and grate the @Garlic Clove{1} (or use a #garlic press{}).

Heat a drizzle of @oil{} in a #large frying pan{} on medium-high heat.

Once hot, add the @Diced British Chicken Breast{260%g} and season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Stir-fry until browned all over, ~{5-6%minutes}.

> IMPORTANT: Wash your hands and equipment after handling raw chicken and its packaging.

Once the chicken is browned, stir in the garlic, @Curry Powder Mix{1%tsp} and @Mango Chutney{40%g} to coat the chicken and cook for ~{1%minute}.

Pour the @Water for the Sauce{100%ml} into the #chicken pan{} (see pantry for amount) and stir in the @Chicken Stock Paste{10%g}. Add the green beans and bring to the boil, then reduce the heat to medium.

Cover with a #lid{} or #foil{} and simmer until the beans are tender, about ~{5-7%minutes}.

Once the beans are tender and the chicken is cooked, remove the lid and stir in the @Soured Cream{150%g}.

Bring to the boil, then remove from the heat. Taste and add @salt{} and @pepper{} if needed. Add a splash of water if a little thick.

> IMPORTANT: The chicken is cooked when no longer pink in the middle.

When ready, fluff up the rice with a #fork{} and share between your bowls.

Spoon your coronation chicken curry over the top and tuck in.

Enjoy!